05596nam a22008175i 9780812292183DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)952799640  a97808122921837 a10.9783/97808122921832doi  a(DE-B1597)452793  a(OCoLC)933515937  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBV1470.G7bW38 2016eb 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a268.0941/090222231 aWaters, Claire M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTranslating "Clergie" :bStatus, Education, and Salvation in Thirteenth-Century Vernacular Texts /cClaire M. Waters. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. Translating Clergie in the Thirteenth Century -- tChapter 1. The Face and the Mirror: Teachers and Students in Conversation -- tChapter 2. Teaching Death: Narrative Assimilation and the Point of Distinction -- tChapter 3. Last Among the First: Salvation, Status, and Reversal in L’Évangile de Nicodème -- tChapter 4. Getting the Riffraff into Heaven: Jongleurs, Whores, Peasants, and Popular Eschatology -- tChapter 5. Queen of the Rabble, Empress of Clerks: Learning Humility in Marian Miracles -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Translating "Clergie", Claire Waters explores texts in French verse and prose from England and the Continent that respond to the educational imperative implicit in the Fourth Lateran Council's mandate that individuals be responsible for their own salvation. These texts return repeatedly to the moment of death and individual judgment to emphasize the importance of the process of teaching and to remind teacher and learner of their common fate.The texts' focus on death was not solely a means of terrifying an audience but enabled lay learners to envision confrontations or conversations with dead friends, saints, or even God. Such dialogues at the point of death reinforced the importance of the dialogue between teacher and learner in life and are represented in such varied works as doctrinal handbooks, miracles of the Virgin Mary, retellings of the Harrowing of Hell, and even fabliaux—tales of wit and reversal—in which it is possible to argue one's way into Heaven. Lively stories that featured minstrels dicing with saints, friends returning from the dead, and thieves teaching the prophets offered a model for laypeople considering how to put their Christian learning into practice and perhaps to teach others.Rather than being seen as a challenge to ecclesiastical authority, lay learning in these texts is depicted as hopeful, comic, and affectionate. By examining informal works of Christian instruction used outside institutional teaching contexts to convey the learning of the schools to the parishes, Waters shows how lay learners could assume the role of disciple or student in a way previously available only to monks or university scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristian educationzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500yTo 1500. 0aChristian educationzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian educationzFrance, NorthernxHistoryyTo 1500yTo 1500. 0aChristian educationzFrance, NorthernxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian literature, FrenchzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian literature, FrenchzFrance, NorthernxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z